## $VER: Tasker.guide v1.00 (18.3.96)

## ars est celare artem

@node Main "Tasker"

	Welcome to the Tasker v1.00 User Guide.
	~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This is only a quick reference guide to Tasker. The program is working but not to the extent that I originally intended. In fact, I would liked to merged the whole program into On-Time and since I am leaving the Amiga scene for a little while, this seems unlikely at the moment.

Tasker was designed to keep track of every-day Tasks. Each task is assigned a priority of either Lowest, Low, Normal, High or Highest. The Tasks appear in a list form and are displayed in order of priority and date.

You may choose to display either All Tasks, Today's Tasks, Future Tasks, Completed Tasks or Overdue Tasks by using the 'Display' cycle gadget in the main window.

A new Tasks is created by clicking 'New' from the main window. Editing a Tasks is performed by selecting one from the list and clicking 'Edit' or double-clicking one. An Edit Window will appear.The program is 'multi-threaded' so you may have as many Edit Windows open at one time as memory permits.

A Task may be marked as 'Completed' by selecting one or a number of entries in the list and clicking on 'Complete' or by selecting the check mark gadget in an Edit Window.

A button labelled 'Chart,' in the main window, will open up an alternative display window. This is only an experimental function and was still in development at time of release. It will open a window with a MUI 'Virtual' gadget showing a time line over the period of a year. Each 'displayed' Task is shown with a TimeLine Bar to the right.  If the Tasks has no beginning date then the Bar extends to the left with a '~' symbol, the same goes for the End date. If the Task begins before the start of the chart Time Line then it begins with a '-'. If the Tasks ends after the end of the Time Line then it will be displayed with a '+' symbol. Tasks that fall outside the chart range completely will be displayed witha '<' or '>' symbol. You may click on any of the rows and the Task's info will be displayed at the top of the window in a text gadet.

From the main window you can click on the 'Config' button and the Config Window will open. From here you may set the format of dates entered and displayed. You may switch off the Main Gadgets in the main window, turn user confirmation of remove requests and cause Tasker to be iconified instead of quiting when the main window is closed. There are also provisions for altering the fundamental colours and font for the Chart. The settings in the Config Window are saved as Tooltypes in the Tasker icon.

Without going into detail, Tasker has a few ARexx commands as well. They are:

   Active      ENTRY/N,NOACTIVE/S
   GetEntries  (NO ARGS)
   GetActive   (NO ARGS)
   GetField    NUMBER/N
   New         NAME/K,PRIORITY/N/K,BEGIN/K/A,END/K/A,COMPLETED/S,NOTES/K
   EditWindow  (NO ARGS)
   Remove      ACTIVE/S
   Complete    STATE/N,TOGGLE/S
   ClearList   (NO ARGS)
   Open        FILE,MERGE/S
   SaveAs      FILE,ICON/S
   Save        (NO ARGS)
   Use         (NO ARGS)
   LastSaved   (NO ARGS)
   Restore     (NO ARGS)
   Display     TYPE/N
   MainGadgets STATE/N,TOGGLE/S
   RX          FILE,SCRIPT/N/K
  About       (NO ARGS)

Tasker is classified FREEWARE and contains the same legal restrictions as the other programs in the Everyday Organiser archive v1.1.

NOTE: If there is ever another update to the EO system then you can expect that this program will not exist but its functions will be contained within the program On-Time.
@endnode
